04579nam a22007335i 9780226713588DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019044399  a97802267135887 a10.7208/97802267135882doi  a(DE-B1597)570905  a(OCoLC)1181841410  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aP95.82.U6bG885 2020 4aP95.82.U6bG885 2020 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a302.2/097309052231 aGunn, Joshua, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitical Perversion :bRhetorical Aberration in the Time of Trumpeteering /cJoshua Gunn. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b9 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreambling toward Profligacy -- tIntroduction: Eating Poorly, or Ketchup on a Steak -- t1. On Critical Violence -- t2. The Psychoses of Speed, with the Example of Social Networking -- t3. The Perverse Style, with Eventual Reference to Pee-wee Herman -- t4. Showmancing the Presidency: Perverse Genres and the Problem of Judgment -- tConclusion: Don’t Play (with) That -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen Trump became president, much of the country was repelled by what they saw as the vulgar spectacle of his ascent, a perversion of the highest office in the land. In his bold, innovative book, Political Perversion, rhetorician Joshua Gunn argues that this “mean-spirited turn” in American politics (of which Trump is the paragon) is best understood as a structural perversion in our common culture, on a continuum with infantile and “gotcha” forms of entertainment meant to engender provocation and sadistic enjoyment. Drawing on insights from critical theory, media ecology, and psychoanalysis, Gunn argues that perverse rhetorics dominate not only the political sphere but also our daily interactions with others, in person and online. From sexting to campaign rhetoric, Gunn advances a new way to interpret our contemporary political context that explains why so many of us have difficulty deciphering the appeal of aberrant public figures. In this book, Trump is only the tip of a sinister, rapidly growing iceberg, one to which we ourselves unwittingly contribute on a daily basis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCommunicationxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aDonald J. Trump.  aFreud.  aLacan.  acritical theory.  acultural studies.  amedia ecology.  aperversion.  apolitics.  apsychoanalysis.  arhetoric.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226713588423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226713588.jpg  a978-3-11-069309-6  UChP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070472-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-PLWb2020